segments.text: was commenting about Mr. Rutter's tenure as president of the university.
My point is not to make too strong a point of the fact that he wasn't the ideal president.
There can be no ideal president for anybody, I suspect, although my feeling now is that President Williams is doing an unusually good job.
But from the standpoint of the faculty, I assume that he's also
been a good job from the standpoint of many of the students.
He's not as visible in many ways as Mr. Rutter was.
Mr. Rutter was completely accessible.
You could go see him almost a moment's notice, and many of us did in those days.
The main point I guess I'm making in regard to Mr. Rutter is that he was a strong leader.
and he did things with conviction.
It's just that not everybody agreed with his convictions.

This is not surprising, and my point is not to disparage him gratuitously at all, or to disparage him in any sense, but to indicate that it's well known in the history of A&M that the faculty was at times, especially certain elements of the faculty, certain groups, I guess maybe the Young Turks, or whatever you want to, how you want to put it,
were at odds with Mr.
Rudder.
We were not always in great harmony with him.

And since this is a matter of history, it would be foolish for me to say otherwise and not to make a point of the fact that one of the activities that was going on, one of the important activities that was going on in the days from 1962 that I'm aware of up into even the late 60s or perhaps middle and late 60s,

or whatever, I don't know when it began to tail off, were activities in which we were appealing to Mr. Rutter to make certain changes in matters involving faculty participation in university governance and having students participate more directly in matters involving various policy.
and so forth.
And the matter of tenure, for example, came up, and it was a great, almost as if it were a surprise to some people in the administration that tenure even existed.
Now, people have different opinions about tenure, I realize that, but tenure was, in fact, an issue for a lot of people, and it became a rather critical issue for some people in the 1960s.
And there were lots of
not lost, but a few cases where these tenure situations became crucial.
And as you know, possibly now, Union is still on what's called the AUP censured list.
And I don't know how it will ever get off of it.
I don't know what the situation is now.
But that happened back in the 60s when
there were some problems with a particular faculty member who appealed for help and got help.
And the A&M administration was found deficient in its handling of his case.
As a matter of fact, it was a very careful investigation, and that's the way it stands to this day.
Now, there's a new administration, to be sure, and in fact, a new spirit.
And I doubt that that sort of thing will ever happen again.
But the fact is, even though that sort of did happen, and then it was changed in that regard remarkably.
I think it would be rather remiss of me not to mention that this sort of thing did happen.
And not again, I should hasten to say, to disparage Mr.
Rudder or to tarnish any memory of him.
He was a likable man.
I enjoyed him personally.
Not always, but frequently I did.
He had a certain ingenuity, a certain frank spirit about him.
He would talk to you man to man.
And he was, no question about it, a leader of people.
But I didn't always agree with the way he led the people.
I thought that would be worth clarifying.
We got into it in the last part of the tape.
Now, you probably have some more direct questions you'd like to ask me, Scott.
Right.
When you came back from the University of Missouri, back down to A&M, and you've mentioned the changes in the university, what were the main changes in that?
community in the Bryan College Station area, and also not only in the physical sense, but also in the population sense?
And what were some of the factors that affected that you could see?
Well, first of all, of course, one of the remarkable things that seemed to happen, even in the time that we were gone,
for those years to the Midwest and came back in 62.
There was a change in the, there was a very noticeable change in the total population of College Station in Bryan.
New things were built.
There was a skyscraper in Bryan, I think,
eight, ten stories high, the Virisco building, which as I remember wasn't there, I'm not sure when it was built, but that's a big building, you know.
Not really a big building by some standards, but a new big building was built.
Well, the number of people was increasing remarkably and has increased remarkably since 1962, as everyone knows.
The two communities merged completely
They may have been merged in the old days, but they weren't really physically that way.
They may have had city limits that were in common, but now they're literally contiguous cities.
You can't tell unless you saw the city limits sign where one starts and the other ends.
That's a remarkable change.
Both cities have changed in that regard.
Industry-wise, I don't know a lot about that, but there isn't an awful lot of industry in either town.
There's a little bit more in Bryan, of course, for fairly obvious reasons, I guess.
It has sought an industry slightly more vigorously.
And obviously, College Station's industry is A&M.
can be, apparently, indefinitely.
As far as the spirit of things around here is concerned, there's been a very progressive spirit.
Let me mention this.
This is an indicator.

There was a time, not too long ago, in fact, since 1962, when you would drive along the North Gate area on University, what's now called University Drive, and I guess always has been, but I had forgotten what it was called.
It had some name, FM, former market road 60, maybe.
But the Northgate area was actually sort of a depressed area in a way, frankly, to me.
I didn't think it looked at all progressive.
The storefronts weren't well kept up.
Things kind of came and went.
It looked very much like a small central Texas town.
Not to disparage small central Texas towns, but they don't look...
If you look at the typical one,
Let's take, oh, I don't know, Caldwell.
Caldwell's a nice little town, but do you remember anything distinct about downtown Caldwell?
It's not really, there are a few, there's a hardware store, some filling stations, a drug store, too, where you can get coffee and toothpaste and Photoshop, maybe, or that sort of thing.
Well, that's kind of what the North Gate was.
It wasn't anything very special about it, except there were, well, there used to be some cafes over there.
I don't think, maybe there still are, but I remember distinctively one or two that I thought were acceptable.
Little places to get breakfast in the morning if you needed to, go over early.
But it was generally a rundown.
It didn't look progressive.
It looked like, what's the word?
Depressed area, something like that.
Whereas now, I think the Northgate area is really spruced up, relatively speaking.
You could say more, but it's doing, I think, very, very well.
And the general spirit of things, I think, is reflected in that.
You see new...
and thriving things on Texas Avenue and all around A&M.
And I suppose that's just what happens when there are more people and there are more customers.
There's more prosperity for those who cater to the customers.
I'm not sure that all follows, but that's just the way I see it, simple way.

So I would say that the general air here has gotten to the general spirit of things has gotten more, a good deal more progressive, and there seems to be more obvious pride in the appearance of things.
And that pleases me.
I'd rather have it that way than have it appear to be a depressed area.
Now, the South Gate section is developing much more slowly.
For reasons I don't understand, there's not as much going on over there.
People move in and out with fabric stores and a couple filling stations.
It used to be that North Gate wasn't a very different spirit from the South Gate area.
I'm talking about beyond the tennis courts.
There's a nice tennis shop over there, and that's marvelous.
It just overruns, and I think that's one of my favorite places in the world.
But that's not enough to sustain the community over there.
There's a need for other things, I would guess.
Of course, the Redmond Terrace area services the community, and that's pretty fancy now with the Aikenland Inn and
And across the street, Holiday Inn and all those things.
That takes the place of anything that would have developed in the so-called South Gate, what might have been called the South Gate area.
Maybe isn't.
Maybe never will be now because it's superseded by the Redmond Terrace area, the Culpepper, the new Culpepper Center.
That's fine.
It's OK with me.
I like to see progress in that sense.
And I think it helps everybody to be more comfortable and to enjoy this community.
I like the old-fashioned way, too.
But if the old-fashioned way means looking depressed, then I don't particularly like that.
The growth of Bryan College Station, a lot of it can be attributed directly to A&M with this growth and more students coming.
But do you see that the growth is playing off of the increase in A&M's enrollment or do you just see something else that's bringing people to Bryan College Station?
I'm not sure I'm qualified to answer that.
Maybe this will be a partial answer, though.
I do feel that A&M's decision to allow coeducation here was a very smart move and a very timely move.
I don't know whether you're aware of it, and I'm just only remotely aware of it, but other universities

Many other universities in the country, and perhaps most other universities in the country, have declining enrollment, whereas A&M is enjoying, if that's the word for it, is at least experiencing rather remarkable increasing enrollment.
A&M is a very popular place to come, as well as a good place to come, fortunately.
My son will go to A&M, and I wouldn't choose another school in the state for him to go to.
I'm glad he wants to go here.
It turns out this is where he wants to go to school.
But I'm just tickled.
I'm very pleased.
I mean, if he had chosen some other school in Texas, I would have been disappointed, frankly.
And I don't know whether we could have afforded it either, but that's beside the point, momentarily.
He likes to go to A&M.
He likes the idea of going to A&M for good reasons.
It's academically very strong.
It's a good community of students that attract him.
He likes the type of students that are here, and everything he knows about the school is positive, and that's just fine.
That's what I feel.
I would have recommended A&M to him if we had lived in Missouri, for example, if we could have afforded to send him to A&M, because I think it's a good school.
Now, I think A&M is a better school now because, frankly, we do have co-education here.
I think having girls to participate in things here, fortunately the girls that come here have the Aggie spirit.
It seems to me they do.
I mean, I think we've got some real great girls here, and I'm very pleased with the co-eds.
I think they're...
I don't know them all, of course.
I know a few.
I get to know them in Physics 350, because we have a few co-eds in there.
And I'm pleased that they're here.
And I'm pleased that they can be in the core and participate in as important an organization as that is.
They seem not to be in any way disorienting or
fouling up the core, as far as I can tell.
They're good spirited gals, and I don't know a lot about that, frankly, but I see no, I may be wrong, but it seems to me that they're not causing any serious problems.
They're not, so to speak, changing the core from the greatness it has always had, as far as I can tell.
And I think having girls come here on just a routine basis and accommodating them in dormitories was a very important move for A&M.
And my guess is, in answer to your question now more directly, that having coeducation here has changed the community in various ways, sometimes indirectly, sometimes directly, as anything else.

I think there are people who come to A&M now who wouldn't come otherwise, who would want to be at a good school like this, but who would rather see a more balanced social life, more balanced than would be normally here if it were just all male.

And that, of course, brings more students, and it helps bring a diversity of businesses or stores that accommodate young ladies with special kinds of clothing, I suppose, and things that are feminine, whereas otherwise we wouldn't have that.
That accommodates the wives of people who have to live here and enjoy living here.
And so it goes.
There must be many chains of
cause and effect, which are related to the admission of girls to A&M.
And I'm very pleased that it's happened.
I think it was inevitable, but I'm glad it happened when it did, because we now are growing and doing well.
What do you think about it?
I think it's pretty good.
Dr. Dunn, I know you have a
meeting you have to go to, and I appreciate your time.
I appreciate you letting me interview you for this project.
Well, thank you very much, Scott.
It's a pleasure to participate and hope it's some help to you.
I'm sure it will be, sir.
Thank you.
You bet.
